Why does Amazon allow people to review products that don't exist? Somehow not only do they allow such things, but they actually sent me an e-mail suggesting I review this pre-ordered, non-existent product. (FYI, it's now February 12, 2014. The show begins April 19, 2014 and who knows when this DVD set is coming out? I figured by pre-ordering I'll get a good price by ordering as soon as possible.)

So, is this DVD set any good? Well, the first season was great but as I write it's the only season there is so far. So . . .

No idea. But I'll give this product four stars. Perhaps it deserves five. After all, no joke, season one was a truly great show and I was just blown away by it. If you haven't seen it, well, a) go see it as soon as possible, and, b) why are you checking reviews for the second season of the show when you haven't checked out the first yet? GO SEE THE FIRST SEASON!! IT'S FANTASTIC!!!

So, normally I'd give it five stars. --But I'll only give it four stars because . . . because it doesn't exist! I think that for a product to achieve five star perfection, well, it must be real, tangible and existent. Otherwise, well . . . it's about as good as that new novel that I haven't written yet.

(But, hey, don't blame me. Amazon's computer specifically *requested* that I review this because it saw I pre-ordered it! I'm only doing as asked.))

Anyway, I have seen the leaked writers' notes for the upcoming season.

I loved the part where the clones all hosted SNL. The part where they all died was upsetting though. I cried for weeks.

And, finally, if you haven't checked out season one, go do so. If you have, chances are you'll check out season two as well.

However, his ability to interact differently with the various clones is genuinely impressive (his interactions with Alison are consistently hilarious).

This show probably fails in my eyes partly because it was the next one I decided to watch after having watched Mr. Robot and Westworld. Those shows have excellent writing, great acting by their entire casts and lavish production. This one doesn't measure up to those.

Tatiana makes deep characters that have a history the milisecond they appear on screen.  I have NEVER in my life seen an actress accomplish what she has.  You have to see it to believe it.

On top of it, I love every character in the show.  Well acted, well written, so much cool variety.  Investigations, plot twists, character developments, it has it all. Given my disappointment with the second season, I won't bother trying the third season of Orphan Black.

I'm reviewing the series from the start to the end of season two.  The series starts a little slowly, so give it five or six episodes and then you'll be hooked.  The intrigue and interwoven plot lines are reminiscent of Person of Interest, which also took five or six episodes to mature into full bloom.

Minor spoiler alert if haven't watched season one:  Tatiana Maslany deserves an Emma nomination for her roles.  She is completely convincing in each of her many roles.  When she plays one of her roles badly attempting to impersonate one of her other roles, you get to see how completely she compartmentalizes her roles, being able to convincingly portray a role unconvincingly pretending to be a role that she plays all the time.  Almost mind boggling.

By season two you think you've got all the players kind of sorted out, only to be thrown a few new curves.  Looking forward to jumping into Season Three.

This is a fascinating production.  The actress, Tatiana Maslany, is amazing.  When I was first told about this production by a friend, the subject matter seemed strange and of no interest to me. I understand Season 4 is something one must pay for, which seems strange as the first three were included as part of the Prime Subscription.  As this is the first streaming I've done using Amazon, I wish they had just included the whole series.  I will definitely be checking this type of thing out before I watch anything else.  It didn't feel right to find out that after you've watched three seasons, you couldn't watch the ending without a charge.  Other than that, I'd recommend this as one of the best productions out there.

This season and this series show will keep you on your toes from start to finish. Tatiana Maslany is a revelation as the main character(s) and has been nominated for an Emmy in both 2015 & 2016. Forget all that hype, watch the show and see for yourself, you will not be disappointed. Orphan Black is not your typical sci-fi thriller; it's unpredictable, seriously you've got to pay attention to keep track; it's inventive and contemporary; and it's funny, I was pleasantly surprised (it kind of reminded me of Fringe in that regard). This show puts The Blacklist and Blindspot to shame, but the main reason to watch is the star, Tatiana Maslany, and the range this woman has in her presentation of the 6 clones that inhabit the Orphan Black world.

This is the most amazing series, due in large part to the incredible performance(s) of Tatiana Maslany. Watching a scene between Sarah and Helena it's sometimes hard to accept that they're both being played by the same actress - even when you're constantly reminding yourself. She not only plays 9 separate and distinct clones so far (with 2 more still to come), but to increase the level of difficulty, she also plays the clones impersonating each other. Sarah pretending to be Rachel is not quite Rachel, but in a different way than Alison pretending to be Rachel. Cosima as Alison slightly off but in a way that lets you "see" Cosima behind Alison. It's truly amazing.

It's said that Spencer Tracy once appeared on stage in a play where he was supposed to be stranded on a desert island in the second act and he "acted" unkempt and unshaven to the point where people wondered how he got his make-up done that quickly. Tatiana Maslany accomplishes something similar. Cosima is thinner and prettier than the other clones. Helena is thicker and more solid. Alison is the most petite. Sarah taller. And then there's Tony.

Orphan Black is not just a one woman show, however. Jordan Gavaris is wonderful as her "brother" Felix, supportive to all the clones and never complaining as he takes a back seat to the force of nature that is Sarah Manning. The other supporting actors, too, are always interesting, whether it's Mrs. S proving again and again that she's hiding much more than she's ever revealed or Detective Bell learning just how little he actually knew about Beth Childs.

A typical episode might have Cosima dying from a genetic disorder, Sarah being chased by murderous assassins, Helena being tortured by religious fanatics and Alison . . . Alison organizing visitation day in rehab or supplying the proper refreshments for her kids' soccer practice. The fact that all 4 story lines are equally compelling is a sign of the quality of the show's writing and production. This is must see TV.

Complication upon complication. There's no questioning the story engineering on this show, and as everybody knows, Tatiana Maslany is the world's greatest victim of Awards Overlook. However, after going through the whole first season and part of the second, I can't help getting weary of how overwrought it is. No matter how much is happening or how high the emotional stakes, the directors seem to feel that you can never have enough melodramatic dialog, pounding music, scowling if not frantic actors, intense composition and editing, etc. Dialing it back and trusting in the situation to keep the viewer on the hook--or even just modulating it a little--just doesn't seem to occur to them. Too bad, since this is a BBC America production. Maybe they felt obliged to amp it up for America.

This season was actually BETTER than season one. I honestly didn't think it was possible for me to become more intrigued with this show than I already was; but Orphan Black gets better with each episode. I want Felix for my own screwed up but overwhelmingly compassionate and loyal brother. Mrs. S is a triumph of the gun-toting, murderously protective, secret keeping foster mother character. And Tatiana Maslany is absolutely masterful in her portrayal of a numerous group of clones. This actor is so good that the viewer can tell right away which character Tatiana is playing by a single micro-expression on her face. This isn't science fiction or in any way strange. It is pure, addictive, self-indulgent drama. My daughter and I count the hours when we have to wait for the next episode to air. If you aren't watching Orphan Black yet, why the hell not??!!?

It is difficult to write about Orphan Black with the clarity and precision it deserves. It is from episode to episode immaculately paced and completely engaging. Character development is uniformly complex and complete.  Across the first three seasons, it is not easy to find comparable storytelling that spins such heightened dramatic tension and brings the characters into such vibrant relief.

I like Orphan Black because it picks up a point in our reality today that is not talked about much, that is cloning. Like Person of Interest, it clues us in on real time events that, unless something earth shattering happens with it, most people pass over it without much, if any thought. I like programs that explore parts of our reality that we give little thought to but exists and impacts how we live and will live our lives. The story line of Orphan Black is interesting and sometimes perplexing with the twists and turns. Alaina, my favorite is offbeat, a little psychotic and helariously funny and incredibly sad. At first, I thought the adding of the male clones was a stretch; however, it would be logical that if scientist could clone females, why not males as well. Sometimes the story line gets bogged down. But in light of what regular TV is offering up as entertainment, I will take a show like Orphan Black any day, hands down. It's different and well acted by Tatiana Maslany. I marvel how she plays each clone so convincingly with each being so unique and quirky. And the technology and level of brain power to bring this all together. Amazing.

This might be my favorite series of all time. Tatiana Maslany does an incredible job of acting all the different versions of herself. As another reviewer mentioned, most amazing is the way when she's playing Hilary impersonating Sarah or Sarah impersonating Rachel, that's exactly what you see, not Tatiana playing either Sarah or Rachel. Her portrayal of each of the different characters is so well-developed and unique that Hilary impersonating Sarah has just the right level of "wrongness" relative to the normal Sarah character to be convincing as a Hilary trying to do the stand-in. I'm not at all one to wax euphoric over actors' performances, but Maslany is absolutely masterful here. I think it's one of the most impressive examples of the craft of acting I've ever seen. Oh - the story and plot line is engaging and fun as well, with bits of nicely understated humor here and there. Very highly recommended.

I give 3 stars because the first 6 episodes are so tedious, they even make Felix boring.  When Allison, the most humdrum character becomes the most interesting one, you know there are issues. The premise seems to be based on the question of nature vs. nurture- "who would you be if you were not in the life you currently know?"  So you might be uptight, totally mellow, a cop or a criminal (all versions of the clone in the show). Skinner said, "Give me a child and I will give you back a thief, a pope or a poet."  This show takes that idea of operational conditioning and runs it in a conspiracy filled way, adds twists, drama and intrigue and spits out Orphan Black. This series just keeps getting better and better as the characters of Sarah Manning and her "sisters" reveal more of their histories and the plot twists keep piling up.
I'm not sure exactly where the series is headed - and that's a good thing. The reason: The problem with many contemporary television programs, in my opinion, is that after a season of surprises subsequent seasons begin to get predictable. It's as though the writers have run out of ideas and are only continuing the program because they have a network deal and contract obligations to fulfill. This is not the case - at least so far - with "Orphan Black." Season 2 contained at least as many surprises as the first season and perhaps a few more. A transgender "sister?" A killer who is good with children? A little girl who seems almost too good to be true? A much younger "sister?" A parallel experiment with men instead of women? Reunions, bar fights, kidnappings... this season has all that and more; full of fresh ideas, push-the-envelope story lines, and terrific acting not only by series star Tatiana Maslany but the rest of the cast as well add up to a wonderful bloc of episodes.
One quick note: Although the nominal heroine of the series is Sarah Manning, I have to say that her "sister" Helena is rapidly becoming my favorite clone. Granted, she's homicidal and as unstable as a bowl of Jell-O, but she is also vulnerable and endearing in many ways. She reminds me a lot of Helen King, the protagonist in novelist Sharon Brownlie's book "Betrayal," because when she is wronged she goes after those that have harmed her with a take-no-prisoners fierceness that is rarely seen on television. Add to that the fact that Maslany has an almost uncanny ability to portray her as something more than a homicidal maniac and you have a character that is unique in television programming.
The verdict: A great season that is probably even better than the first.

Orphan Black's second season is as much a masterpiece as the first. Good job, everybody! I'm kinda picky, but the writing, plotting, pacing, and the acting continue to be absolutely top notch. No spoilers, but Tatiana Maslany just keeps getting more and more amazing, in all her roles. Acting-wise, she can apparently do pretty much anything -- and I really do mean ANYthing!
In fact, all the actors are awesome, across the board, and manage the sometimes-absurdly-quirky twists and turns of the plot without breaking stride. However incredibly unlikely the situation, the actors pull it off -- make you believe it.

And now, as the plot continues to thicken, emotions intensify, and the stakes escalate, I've got my fingers crossed that the whole ensemble can keep the quality soaring for the third season.

Thanks Amazon, for offering this quality of content.

Uneven. The show is so uneven. Spoilers are here. When it is brilliant it is truly so, and there is enough of that to keep you watching. Tatiana Maslany is certainly incredible and deserves her Emmy. I am not sure if it's Helena or Alison who makes me laugh harder, and the bounce from tragedy to comedy is unrelenting, so for me the show is hard to binge on. I can only take one episode at at time. Some of the plot flaws become so glaring there have been a few episodes when I am on the verge of giving up and discarding the whole show, and then Alison does something so hilarious, or Helena something so outrageous that I find myself cheering and laughing aloud. So I am still in the mix. The advent of the male version is a mistake. Too much, too far, over the top, silly. That's one that made me consider giving up on the show. There is so much to do already with the characters and the plot line and the corporate threat that this silly addition becomes ludicrous and stupid. Of course Sarah and Felix when they have the screen are incomparable and wonderful.

I am not a sci-fi fan. As a result, I skipped watching this show when it first came out. Clones? Not interested. Really bad season so far. I'm on episode 6 of Season 2 of "Orphan Black," and it's a struggle! To be honest I feel like this season is pure garbage, but according to the Amazon reviews 83% of more than 11,000 people gave season 2, 5 stars. To me, that means there is something that I'm missing. Unfortunately 6 episodes in, and I'm still missing it. The main story line for this season is so slow, and a lot [and I mean a lot] of the sub-plots and character behavior doesn't make any sense. For instance, Helena is a mentally deranged mass murderer. Why is Sarah trusting her? or talking to her? or not actively figuring out a way to turn her over to Interpol? I don't know. I mean, also, where is the law in all of this? I feel like the Death Star could open fire on half of the town, and the police would ignore it. Because you know... reasons. I'm not trying to be a troll, but I feel like this season is just pure garbage. Everything happens with soap opera convenience. No one asks any questions. People show up at the right times, say the right things, don't die from major crashes, and loads of other ridiculous and unbelievable stuff. I'm going to finish this season on an upcoming weekend when I have time again, but, I can't recommend this season to anyone.

Also, Season 2, Episode 5, "Ipsa Scientia Potestas Est." I don't care if the character Paul didn't say 'No' -- Rachel is a rapist. Black-mailing Predator Rachel didn't even let 'No' be an option for Paul.

Tatiana Maslany is a master of lead and character acting, which makes this show tremendously fun to watch. Were it not for her strength playing most of the major roles in the show, it easily could have flopped. I predict a long career for her when the show one day wraps up. As an American, I was not familiar with her work, although I gather she has a had a few other roles in Canada.

On the show itself, I'll just say it's refreshing to see a well done science fiction program. Too often the category is relegated to campy, low budget productions for the Sci-Fi channel. Orphan Black elevates the sci-fi TV program to a viable vehicle. I hope it will lead to more programming in the category.

I am a late bloomer concerning Orphan Black. When season 1 first began I set it up on my DVR figuring it was a new and exciting Sci-Fi show. After a few episodes of clones without knowing the whys or hows, I stopped watching. To many unanswered questions. Fast forward to 2015-16 and I've just concluded seasons 1 and 2. I am now hooked. What caused the turn-around? Primarily, the superb acting of Tatiana Maslany and her supporting cast (especially the young girl who plays her daughter). If an Oscar could be given for a TV series, Ms. Maslany would be up for best actress. She has done an outstanding job bringing humanity, pathos, and believability to all the characters she plays. I actually feel I'm watching clones even though intellectually, I know I'm not. A great example is episode 10 of season 2. The sister clones dance and each one dances differently depending on the type of character.

The story line contains enough suspense and conspiracy theory to keep X-Files afficionados happy. Spoilers - what is known after season 2 is a corporation is trying to clone females and a part of the military is trying to clone males. Female clones cannot have children (except Sarah who is a "failure" and has given birth to a daughter). That is why she is a scientific oddity and people are willing to do whatever is necessary to understand why she is different and what makes her and her daughter's physiology tick.

I need a short break from the suspense and then I will enthrall myself with season 3. Give the series a chance. I think you will find the show a must watch.

What will happen once human cloning becomes scientifically feasible?

That question is addressed with chilling logic in BBC America's superb sci-fi thriller Orphan Black as it enters into its second season. And it ain't pretty.

Tatiana Maslany plays multiple roles as clones - we've met seven so far - created by a powerful conglomerate named Dyad and its scary head scientist, Aldous Leekie (Matt Frewer).

Set in Toronto, Orphan Black is told principally through the eyes of one of the clones, English-born grifter and single mother Sarah Manning.

The story opened last season as a fascinating mystery. At loose ends for money, Sarah one day witnesses an identical-looking woman, police detective Beth Childs, commit suicide. Intending only to empty her bank accounts, Sarah grabs Beth's wallet and keys and assumes her identity. She soon finds herself enmeshed in a deadly conspiracy.

Beth had discovered she was one of more than a half dozen clones, human beings owned by Dyad - the company holds the patent on their DNA. Sarah also learns that Dyad has kept tabs on the clones since birth by inserting its agents into their lives to become their husbands, lovers, and friends.

Maslany is riveting as the different clones, each with her own look, her own idiosyncracies, quirks, and speech patterns.

There's Alison Hendrix, an uptight, pill-popping suburban housewife and amateur actress; Cosima Niehaus, a brilliant if whacked-out genius scientist; Helena, a crazed serial killer; and the scariest clone of them all, Rachel Duncan, the heartless executive who runs Dyad's Toronto offices.

As if Dyad weren't bad enough, we find out in the second-season opener that a group of religious fundamentalists has decreed that the women are less than human and deserve to be killed.

Orphan Black, like all great works of science fiction, provides us with an imaginative exploration of how scientific advances alter our world, how new tech raises moral questions and affects every facet of our social, political, and economic life.

Brilliantly written and photographed, it's as thrilling, exciting and groundbreaking as The X-Files was in its era.

This is a show that I've always wanted for so long but nothing was ever made of. I love the idea of clones in sci-fi films and tv shows and then this show happened. This season continued with where it left off last season but much better. The season carried on with many hilarious moments mainly between Alison and Donnie. I have to say this season won me over with their love because before I didn't trust him or like him at all AND wanted him gone.

I loved finding out a lot more on how the clones became who they are and what kind of things that went on with the process of cloning people.  Some secrets come out about why the clones are not able to have children and some other secrets come out about rachel which I found interesting. I do not care for here but I also feel for her as the season concluded. She's still a crazy chick!

Sarah is still my favorite but cosima is my close second as she seems more down-to-earth and relatable. I love her dorky side but I do not like her girlfriend daphne I believe her name is. She's not such a bad person but I'd rather cosima be single and focus on herself and finding this cure for this sickness.

Unexpectedly intriguing...I turned this on one night, just for the heck of it, to see what it was like, starting with season 1.  I was surprised that I ended up liking it so much.  One girl plays about 10 different characters, and does so very believably!  She has different accents (all well done) and is amazing with her ability to morph into the various roles seamlessly...a few times, she even plays one of the clones impersonating a different clone, which takes some talent as well...her accents are good enough, that we looked her up online, to see if she was a Brit putting on a believable American accent, or vice versa...we found out that she's Canadian! So, her English accent is excellent, and she even does Russian and Ukranian and you wonder if she's from there because of how well she pulls it off.  I was most perturbed to find out that only the first two seasons are included with Amazon Prime.  They get you hooked into it, and then want to charge $2 an episode to get to see how season 3 plays out...totally poor on their part...season three should be included! I would have rated it 5 stars, if it wouldn't be for this issue.

Terrific storyline & performances, most especially by Tatiana Maslany. A genuine thriller of Bond-like proportions (since Daniel Craig become Bond). Characters are well-developed. On the downside, though Jordan Gavaris as Felix & Maslany as Cosima are 1st rate, enough of gay-ness. The storyline seeks to make a major statement about being gay. It does: It beats viewers about the head & shoulders with his gay lifestyle. It drives it into the ground.

Not everyone; indeed, not even close to everyone, is OK with the gay lifestyle. This viewer included. This is not the same thing as being against gays. This is viewer is not a gay hater/basher.

Orphan Black's storyline does not depend upon, doesn't even need Felix or Cosima, or any other character, to be gay. Their lifestyle is a non-essential plot element.

This is a dense & dark drama centered on the first creation of human clones, with one character portraying eight genetically identical people who have been living completely different lives - until they meet.

thinking them to be a weapon that could control our evolutionary future. Maslany (the lead) does a remarkable job of portraying eight human clones who are genetically identical, but who are living completely different lives - before they eventually meet.

Characters with a wide mix of sexual & gender preferences are richly done - I praise them not for their sexuality but for their several active roles in the drama.

With one actor playing eight roles, I struggled at times with tracking identities, others may not.

Despite that, I say stick with it; through three seasons a lot that was confusing in early episodes later becomes clear.

I'll footnote this: While just fiction (for now), the subtext of this drama raises questions we all may be facing within a few decades.

The entire cast continues to serve serve up stellar performances, with Tatiana Manslany continuing to dazzle the viewer with her amazing performance in multiple roles. It is gratifying to know that in July 2015 she was finally nominated for an Emmy Award. Whether she will win remains to be seen, but she is certainly deserving of the win. That being said,  I can't wait to binge watch season three!

Intricate (but not overly complex) story lines, compelling characters (94% of which are played by one actor) and a thought-provoking premise make for the best show on television today.  The entire cast is extraordinary (particularly Maria Doyle-Kennedy as Mrs. S and the exquisite Evelyne Brochu as Delphine) with Jordan Gavaris giving an incredible, beautifully layered portrayal as Felix - Sarah's foster brother/confidant/partner in crime.

The standout, however, continues to be Tatiana Maslany.  In S2, she brings seven characters to life - not just, "Oh, different hair and clothes means another Clone!"...I mean, a fully realised, fleshed-out person, with their own accent, vocal tone/register, gait and mannerisms. To say that she is in the midst of a tour de force performance is the biggest understatement ever uttered. I often find myself emotionally overwhelmed when watching her work!

First and foremost, Tatiana Maslany continues to do brilliant work in the second season of Orphan Black.  How someone can convincingly play this many different characters and NOT wind up with an Emmy is...well, evidence that the Emmys continue to suck.  Whatever other issues the season may have, every episode is a must-watch simply to enjoy Maslany's multiple performances. In particular, the work she does as Helena, rounding out and humanizing the character, is phenomenal.

That being said, the plot for season 2 was more scattered than the first season's, and it didn't always seem like the show runners had a firm grasp on the big picture.  In many ways it feels like a bridge between season one and season three (which I've not seen because it isn't on Prime yet).

I didn't know what to expect when I first started watching, and I wasn't sure I was going to stick with it after the first couple of episodes of Season 1. However, I'm glad I did because good things come to those who wait. It's like a pot of water on the stove. It needs to increase to a frenzied boil after some time, not right away. That's the payoff. The cast is impressive, but Maslany is amazing in the way she has given every clone her own voice, personality, and quirks. It's about time she got her Emmy nom and now hopefully a win, because she deserves it. My favorite scene was in Felix's flat with all the sisters, even Helena, dancing together. It was sweet, touching, and flawlessly filmed. I hope Prime will make Season 3 available soon, because I can't wait to find out what's going to happen next. Bravo, Orphan black!

This is an engrossing series with some excellent characters and spot-on acting.  I think it falls short of 5 stars because some episodes are sketchy  with story continuity and you can lose track of what's going on (even binge watching it) at times.  It may just be the British storytelling style, but I found it a little disconcerting.  Other than that, the other issue I had was that yes, human cloning is illegal, and yes, human clones are treated as animals by their governments (in this story), but I found myself not being able to work up the same frenzy over the ethics that the writers of this show seem to be in.  Muddying the waters is one character who is a clone, but in a high-ranking government position who theoretically would be in an excellent position to either promote the bright future of human clones, or to bring down the whole operation.  She seems to not be in either position, and it's difficult to track her motivations, which is a distraction to the show.  Stellar character performances by Tatiana Maslany, as she plays ALL the female clone parts extremely consistently, which is no small feat considering all the clone characters are digitally pasted in with one another requiring extensive use of green screen and doubles.  Good directing!  I like the overall production sheen of this show, and the use of single camera scenes judiciously and appropriately.  It kept me watching it for 3 nights of 2 seasons!

A sci-fi series without aliens or blasters or lots of CGI? Yes, just good speculative writing. The very talented lead actress plays 11 different roles with some remarkable green screen technology and en excellent supporting cast including the former Max Headroom, Matt Frewer who performed convincingly and characteristically as a good bad guy, or was he a bad good guy? The biotechnology involved is speculative but hardly outlandish and this is some of the most believable science fiction you will see.

Five MYSTERIOUS Stars. ***UPDATE: she FINALLY WON THE EMMY IN A LATER SEASON AS BEST ACTRESS*** Tatiana Maslany continues her brilliant performance and even ups the ante, as does the rest of the cast. Season 2 introduces a number of surprises and characters that keep the tension going through to the end. If you liked the first season of Orphan Black, season two will bend your mind more than Season 1. The producers were brilliant in bringing back the towhead' and introducing new characters such as the Michelle Forbes (Ensign Ro of Star Trek TNG) character. They probably should have kept one of the characters, who came and went very quickly, but otherwise they are making brilliant choices that will keep the audience guessing and give even new revelations, leading to Season 3. There are also continuted great supporting performances by Jordan Gravis, Maria Doyle Kennedy, Dylan Bruce, Kevin Hanchard, Delphine Cormier, Skyler Wexler, and others. Highly Recommended with rating cautions noted below. Buckle up for some amazing scenes. Five MIND-BOGGLING Stars. (BBC. Amazon Instant Video. 10 episodes. Season 2. Rated TV-MA, Color, Closed Captioned. Profanity, gore, and socially-challenging situations. The series is currently in Season 3.)

Good TV if you like SciFi  ish  shows.

A story about human clones in their twenties that are all in very different life situations (punk, soccer mom, corporate VP, violent religious extremist, bio-tech nerd, police offer). When they find out about each other (and some evil plot to kill them all), these extremely different characters (all played by the same actress) start interacting (and sometimes filling in for each other), which makes for amazing and surprising story lines.

I love how it cuts through all the genres, SciFi, thriller, detective story, desperate house wives, hilarious black comedy. Very well done.

What I don't like is that Seasons 1 and 2 were free on Prime, getting me hooked, while Season 3 is only available for purchase (not renting) and rather expensive...

There is no way anyone I mean anyone, would try and get away with impersonating a police officer and detective no less and get away with it.  The beginning could have been made to the more realistic. You just had to ignore what was happening and with zero explanation of how she coped with day to day activities at the station not having one ounce of knowledge made for repeated eye rolls.  But once this foolishness passes the show did become quite good.  The second season had many new developments that carried the show until the last episode and the unveiling of male clones.  But as many other reviewers have already stated it is so confusing as to what exactly is going on and who is on who's side. Of course the writers want you to keep guessing but to this point the only person I am pulling for and who i think will be on Tatiana's side is Paul. Because of all this confusion of what's happening I have not yet decided to watch the third season.  I certainly will not pay to watch it.  On a side note the acting by the star is outstanding (although i do not like the male they made her portray, the last clone).

This TV series is one of the world's best kept entertainment secrets and it really shouldn't be a secret.  The chemistry between characters, even the highly varied characters played by the same actors, is outstanding.  The script appears to move fluidly toward a prearranged, long-term destination that isn't irrationally rerouted at the whim of the writers like many U.S.-based shows that don't appear to be thought out more than one season in advance (e.g. Lost).  Though this is a serial, it thoughtfully concludes certain story lines while injecting future story line possibilities in a way that will keep the audience looking forward to more episodes without leaving the audience hanging from a cliff while waiting for a new season to begin (that often either never begins or has to be drastically rerouted due to unexpected casting changes).

I love the plot and the character development. The only complaint I have is that sometimes when two or more clone characters are in the same frame, it looks kinda fake and weird, and sometimes when their hands interact it doesn't look right, but I understand how difficult it must be to film those kind of scenes. The premise is "Orphan Black" has only learned recently that she is a clone and that there are others like her.  And since the main characters are primarily the clones, only one actress can be used to play the different roles. Tatiana Maslany, who plays the protagonist(s) does an amazing job of portraying different characters without creating stereotypes. Each clone is unique and believable as a full human being. It's impressive she is able to change personas so quickly and completely (I'm assuming each show was shot in sequence).  I would definitely recommend  this for those who are interested in the SciFi/adventure/thriller genre.

Just as good as the first season, largely due to Tatiana Maslany's fantastic skill, as noted so many other reviewers, that it's pointless to even mention it again.  It's amazing how you can love some of the characters she's portraying (like Cosima) and hate others (like Rachel) --- or even both at once (like Helena), or change your opinion about them over time (like Alison) --- and recognize which is which at a glance.  Or have a scene in which she's playing five separate characters (unless I've lost count; maybe four is the max) mutually interacting with each other.  Of course I'm sure that makeup and costuming and just plain camera tricks help out a lot in ways I can't understand, but however they do it, it's seamless and perfect.  It's not *just* Tatiana Maslany, of course, though I doubt the show is even possible without her; the entire cast is quite good, even the characters I hate, and the story is reasonably entertaining, even if not differing tremendously in its basic idea from similar shows like Dark Angel.

I tripped on season one of Orphan black while deployed in Afghanistan and basically binged through it.  The first season I thought was great due to Taiana Maslany, but the sci-fi/suspense/thriller/conspiracy/military cocktail is entertaining great as well.  I think special affects and action sequences are fun to watch like the next person, but a interesting storyline is needed also.  I think with sci-fi/fantasy stories, the "buy in" to the story and the "special effects" don't match, it can either be entertaining or eye-rolling depending on your taste.  I think that is what make the orphan black series relatively unique.  It has the sci-fi storyline of cloning mix in with the ngovernment/military conspiracy without the huge need of special effects.  True there are parts in Orphan Black of the "buy in" can be a reach, but that is with any sci-fi fantasy story and the creators and writers have done a great job.

As for Season Two you won't be disappointed.  If you enjoyed S1 you will like S2.  S1 provided the foundation of the story line along with the various characters/ clones.  S2 I think provides more depth to the various character clones which I think the series has done well without being too serious.  Tatian Maslany is a great talent not only for her looks, but here ability to make all her characters/clones/sisters unique.  Season 2 gave a great cliffhanger at the end have me debate either buying S3 or waiting until in becomes free on Amazon Prime!

I was asked to rate seasons 1 & 2 separately, I did not know how to do that; is 1 better than 2?  I couldn't see the whole broken into two subsets, one compliments the other, the only difference is time, one follows the other; there were no significant changes that set them into two separate genres. I waited to watch all that was available and then formulated one general analysis and critique of the series.

It is, indeed very good, one of the best, I enjoyed it immensely. A new formula with a very talented female performer who is still developing in the art of drama and perhaps, one of these days, become as accomplished as Meryl Streep, I'd like that very much. Her talent is uncanny as she represents these identical clones not alike in character, personality or nature within; when she acts one forgets the other even if two or more are present in the same scene, I was partaken. My favorite character is Helena, a ruthless killer with hidden sensitivity and a heart of gold, her shortcomings are the result of a cruel and misguided upbringing, but down deep she knows the difference between good and evil. La Femme Nikita and Colombiana have nothing on her, they don't even hold a candle to Helena; she's also a survivor of the toughest kind. I hope nothing happens to her, in the last installment of Season 2, she gets abducted by the military and taken into a Hercules transport airplane  to be flown somewhere.

The series could've been first rate, but it is not, to my taste. Some writers, producers and directors can't seem to get the message that if the viewer wants to watch pornography he/she would watch a XXX movie. The explicit sex is totally unnecessary here and even disgusting as in any other production, in fact the best movies have hardly any torrid scenes in them. Euripides, Shakespeare, Moliere and others of the great ones, never seem to have run to this tool to make their plays likeable. I guess filth sells, but not as well as clean art and talent.
For this reason I gave Orphan Black four stars, a great production heavily influenced by the new progressive forces of cinematography.

A truly inspired and original show that encompasses many genres such as, science fiction, drama, and dark humor. Though the entire cast is amazingly talented Tatiana Maslany, in particular deserves recognition for her craft. Her performance as Sara Manning and her numerous clone sisters is absolutely brilliant. Each clone has such individual characteristics that I can scarcely believe one actress is playing all of them. This show is both thought provoking and thrilling. I was on the edge of my seat for every episode and could hardly wait to get to the next one. If you are fan of intelligent TV whether you enjoy science fiction or not this a show that is an absolute must see.

This is one of the best sci-fi dramas I've seen in a very long time, and definitely the best on television right now. The show has excellent plot and character development with each episode going at a fast pace leaving you wanting more. Tatiana Maslany does an amazing job at creating unique characters with their own personalities, which is quite a feat to do in under one script. I also like the clever integration of many current social issues that makes it feel very much "today."

Maybe not quite as exciting or splendidly chaotic as Season 1, but Season 2 still proves that this show is better than most SF, or even dramas in general, on TV. The plot is getting more and more complex without feeling the least bit jumbled, and the writers continue to find new twists and turns to keep intrigue high. Not to mention Tatiana Maslany's beautiful performance is even more spectacular this time around.

One of the things I really love about Orphan Black is the way it explores gender, sexuality and identity issues--and of course the old nature vs. nurture argument. Season 2 does a nicer job of this with perhaps more nuance and intellect than Season 1 did. This, for me, is why this show is one of my favorites on TV right now, and one of the best SF series in a long time.

I love this show for so many reasons.  One, and it cannot be said enough, Tatiana Maslany is a brilliant actress!  I am so impressed by her ability to play different characters with different accents, mannerisms, and facial expressions!  Another reason to love the show?  Science!  This show is about what Science is opening up to us and , not to mention, what may be possible issues in the not too distant future!  And, science is not just about genetics and DNA and cloning but it is also artfully brought down to the level of a child albeit the child is a brilliant little actress herself!  And another reason to love this show?  You just start to believe that you know who is playing on what side and the tables turn.  Every episode you'll need to decide if you want to be on the side of the little bit "bad" or the little bit "good".  Enjoy!

Season one was far more compelling. Season two felt like a lot of repetitive and gimmicky chasing around. Reminded me of the various fetch missions on MMORPGs. I also hate the plot mechanism where people are killed off in various ways only to be ridiculously resuscitated later. Also, the obsession with the child was okay up to a point, but was not believable by the end of the season. Lastly, the Allison storyline got super old and while clearly intended to provide some comic relief, felt rather out of place. In general, story and character development definitely needed some work in this season. I like the premise, though, and definitely enjoyed the first season.

This has got to be one of the best shows I've ever watched and they definitely kept it up for season 2. Tatiana Maslany is an impressive actress. It is always amazing to me when one actress can play such different roles/characters and having you believing each is separate and there are not many actresses that can do it. Usually, I see them on the screen and I'll say - oh, that's so-and-so from ___ and remember her role in that. In Orphan Black, Maslany does such a great job that even when you have multiple clones together, you still can see the differences. The differences are there not only with their accents, but with their diction, and their body language. As far as the storyline, it's got lots of variation to appeal to anyone.

When it comes to entertainment, you tend to know why you like something; it's funny, or poignant, well-written, acted or directed, or a combination of all. Orphan Black is a little harder to figure because it has a way of being occasionally deficient in all relevant categories. It can be laugh-out-loud funny at times (watching housewife Allison trying to deal with something outside of her comfort zone). It can be poignant (recognizing Helena's essential need for family/connection). It's generally well-written (albeit, occasionally confusing). Tatiana Maslany is brilliant in most of her clone characters (Tony's something of a bust). The production qualities are high. Directed by different people, it can suffer from varyingly successful degrees of pace, focus, and the occasional odd moment. Yet for all of this, it is remarkably compelling. . .I read about the production in a recent New York Times Magazine article that focused on Tatiana Maslany, which led me to search out the series' first two seasons in time to watch its third season premiere on Saturday, April 18. I am frankly surprised that it has gone on so long (currently, 22 hours; with commercials) on BBC America without actually revealing the core motive behind the creation of its eight (nine? more?) central characters, all played by Maslany. It's a combination of excellent story-telling, and the occasionally manipulative technique of cliff-hangers that have kept me coming back. Just when I thought, at a variety of moments, that I'd had just about enough of the convoluted and long-drawn-out plot, the writers came up with something that in some cases, made me literally gasp. . "Oh My God. . .!!" It'll be interesting to see if this kind of pace can be sustained throughout its current season. And, inquiring minds want to know, will there ever be a satisfactory resolution; a finish to the tale that will resonate positively with its viewers. It feels like a story that requires an endgame; a point at which Sarah and her 'sisters' are no longer in danger and life goes on. It's not episodic in the way (as random example) that CSI adventures are episodic; different tales centered on a core concept and different cities. To be sure, there are interpersonal back stories to all of the CSI characters in their different cities and it helps to know who's who and their relationship to other series characters, but this doesn't affect the central story of each episode. So far, Orphan Black has been successful in creating something of an onion peel, where increasing layers of information inform the compulsion to keep watching. I suspect this is going to get old pretty soon. How many times can the tale re-wrap itself around some sort of immediate danger to Sarah's daughter, Kira, and the sisters' reaction which cause one or a combination of them to save the day and rescue the grade-school kid. We've been informed by some of the bad guys that Kira is something of a key to their whole scheme (which we still do not know in complete detail). Again, all well and good, but the series has the potential of becoming victim to its own layered complexities. Imagine discovering that Tolstoy had written War and Peace Part II. For all of its sequels and prequels, the Star Wars phenomenon has succeeded because each episode is complete in and unto itself. Yes, it is beneficial to the franchise that viewers come to succeeding productions, armed with some knowledge of the back stories, but you can sit down and watch Return of the Jedi and have a good time without resorting to the original and The Empire Strikes Back. This is not true of Orphan Black. Watching the Season Three opener would expose you to incomprehensible story lines that would frustrate your viewing pleasure.
All this said, if you have interest in this series, go back and start at the beginning.

This show is RIDICULOUS! Once you start watching, you just can't stop. The lead actress is BRILLIANT!!! She has created 5-7 separate and distinct characters (they are all clones, but couldn't be more different from each other) that each has their own compelling storyline. It's stunning that she hasn't been nominated for an Emmy. She should be nominated in the lead actress AND supporting actress categories and should WIN in both. No one else even comes close to matching her work in this series. How is it that there isn't more buzz around this show and this actress in particular? For my money, she's the new 'it' girl(s)!

I just finished the last season and it was very entertaining watching Tatiana play all of the clone sisters though some were much better than others you're never seeing one long enough thats its a problem. The plot is about clones, competing forces, issues and the ever present family and/or domestic crisis. A very good supporting cast keeps it together and if theres a fault it would be the humor is not always present but when it is its a real boost to the show. The last season seemed rushed, over the top and pretty devoid of humor. Its a good sci-fi thriller and through the course of the show it was sometimes hard to tell the same person was playing all the roles because the transformations were so good. Overall, it was a 4-star series but the last one is a real push to give it 3-stars. There are a few characters that I found to be annoying and there was much too much of them toward the end. If nothing else, it was worth it just for the uniqueness of the plot and how well it was done by Tatiana. It took us four years to see the entire series so Im copping out with the same review for each because my mind is too blurry to address each one specifically and if you like the first one you will watch the others despite what anyone has to say about it.
